{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1774643237,"nonce":"PkGucXZuTK/EUpXI/M+k9i8UeZo=","message":"Ambiguity clarification for the issue body:\n\n1. \"Extract the learned adversary parameters from trained models across different SISU levels and training conditions\" — this should specify that it applies to minimax-trained models (Part 2.5 adversarial training), not standard PAI-ASF models (which have no learned adversary). The relevant model configurations from the Tier 1 experiments (issue 3b70482, comment #7) are:\n\n   - GRU additive, single adversary (GaussianBumpAdversary, 3 bumps)\n   - GRU additive, population K=5 adversary\n   - GRU multiplicative, single adversary\n   - GRU multiplicative, population K=5 adversary\n   - vRNN additive, single adversary\n   - vRNN additive, population K=5 adversary\n   - vRNN multiplicative, single adversary\n   - vRNN multiplicative, population K=5 adversary\n\n   All with: 180 hidden units, loss_update ratio=0.3, force_max=2.0, 2000 warmup + 10000 adversarial batches, 5 vmapped replicates.\n\n2. \"Compare adversary strategy across training methods (standard backprop vs CVaR vs APT)\" — standard backprop and CVaR do not have a learned adversary, so this comparison only applies to the different adversary formulations within minimax training (single vs population, different force_max values, etc.). The APT models from Part 2.5 (issue c05998e) used a different adversary mechanism (gradient ascent on perturbation forces, not a parameterized adversary model), so their \"adversary strategy\" would need to be extracted differently (from the worst-case perturbation trajectory rather than from model parameters).\n\nCo-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.6 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e","files":null}]}